	<div id="entry-23">
		<div class="entry-header">
			<!--<h2 class="asset-name entry-title">
Studies Without Borders
</h2>-->
			<div class="entry-meta" title="2009-06-15T14:57:08-05:00">Monday Jun 15, 2009</div>
		</div>
	
		<div class="entry-content">
			<div class="entry-body">
				
<img alt="Megan Putnam" src="http://newsfeed.encs.concordia.ca/encs_test/meg7.JPG" class="mt-image-left" style="margin: 0pt 20px 20px 0pt; float: left;" width="160" height="213" />For recent graduate Megan Putnam, leaving Concordia behind also means leaving Canada behind. This fall, Megan embarks on a 13-month journey to Africa with Engineers Without Borders, the charitable organization dedicated to promoting human development in Africa through access to technology. Having already spent the summer of 2008 posted in Ghana as a short-term volunteer, Megan relishes the opportunity to go back: "That was my first time off the continent and it definitely changed me. It's a completely different way of life. Despite the poverty, everyone is incredibly generous and kind. Ghanaians are also very capable - there is great potential, it's an exciting place to be, and it is gratifying to be part of the change."<br /><br />2009 is a year of milestones for Megan: not only did she graduate with a BEng. (with great distinction) in Civil Engineering from ENCS, she was also chosen to be the faculty's valedictorian. "I was thrilled when I found out," Megan recalls, "even though I was really, really nervous giving my speech." In her valedictory address, delivered to a packed house at Place des Arts during the spring convocation ceremony, Megan focused on the importance of working together to create a global community. "The few hours before I actually got up there, listening to the names, I saw that my classmates were from all over the world. There's such diversity at Concordia," she observes, noting that the global community of which she spoke is already being built by her peers.<br /><img alt="Megan Putnam" src="http://newsfeed.encs.concordia.ca/encs_test/meg4.JPG" class="mt-image-center" style="margin: 0pt auto 20px; text-align: center; display: block;" width="300" height="225" />Shortly after receiving her degree, Megan attended the Soirée de l'excellence of the <a class="zem_slink" href="http://www.oiq.qc.ca/" title="Ordre des ingénieurs du Québec" rel="homepage">Ordre des ingénieurs du Québec</a>, held this year in Sherbrooke. During the gala event, Megan was awarded third place in the Prix Universitaires du Mérite. She was selected on the combined strengths of her grades, her community involvement, and an essay entitled "The Professional Responsibility of Global Engineers as Drivers in the Seat of a Transformative Change Train." Present at the event were Dean of ENCS, Dr. Robin Drew; Associate Dean of External Affairs, Dr. Louise Quesnel; and Associate Dean of Student Academic Services, Dr. Radu Zmeureanu. "It was a great surprise to have them all there!" Also present was Megan's twin sister, who is currently finishing up a degree in Chemical Engineering at Queen's University. Megan plans to donate part of her prize winnings to Engineers Without Borders and to use the rest to fund a relaxing summer before she gears up for her return to Africa.<br /><br />Asked why her time at Concordia was such a success, Megan responds simply: "it was all about getting involved." Her advice to prospective ENCS students is equally to the point: "Take advantage of the opportunities offered to you. Go to events and talk to people. Go to Reggie's on Fridays. Get involved with organizations like Engineers Without Borders or the Engineering and Computer Science Association. Figure out what you're most interested in and learn about different things that are going on. Manage your time well, though, and do your best to excel with your studies." With an attitude like Megan's, it's clear that one can go very far indeed.<br /><br />To learn more about Megan's experiences with Engineers Without Borders, visit her blog at <a href="http://www.meginghana.blogspot.com/">www.meginghana.blogspot.com</a>.<br /><div></div><br />


			</div>
		</div>
	</div>
	
	
	
